ACLED does not have a fatality threshold for event inclusion. This means that conflict and demonstration events in ACLED do not have to produce any fatalities in order to be included as a valid event. We use no arbitrary number of deaths to define a conflict.\\n2. ACLED reports fatalities only when a reputable source has relayed that information. Further, researchers seek out information to triangulate – where and when possible – the numbers from any report.\\n3. ACLED uses the most conservative estimate available, and will revise and correct the totals – upward or downward – when better information comes available.\\n\\nACLED advises caution in using all fatality numbers from its, or any other conflict data source. Fatality information is the most biased, and least accurate, part of any conflict report and extreme caution should be employed when using any fatality number to show patterns.',\n     metadata_modified: '2018-11-17T01:17:00.774855',\n     author: null,\n     author_email: null,\n     subnational: '1',\n     state: 'active',\n     has_geodata: false,\n     methodology: 'Other',\n     version: null,\n     is_requestdata_type: false,\n     license_id: 'cc-by-sa',\n     num_of_showcases: 1,\n     type: 'dataset',\n     resources: [ [Object] ],\n     dataset_preview: 'first_resource',\n     num_resources: 1,\n     dataset_source: 'ACLED',\n     tags: [ [Object], [Object], [Object], [Object] ],\n     revision_id: '12780823-68e3-4ea1-a066-698fae1a16d0',\n     groups: [ [Object] ],\n     creator_user_id: '154de241-38d6-47d3-a77f-0a9848a61df3',\n     has_quickcharts: true,\n     methodology_other: '[ACLED\\'s Methodology page](https://www.acleddata.com/resources/methodology/) contains information about how the ACLED team collects, cleans, reviews and checks event data, with a focus on what makes ACLED unique and compatible with other data. This dataset contains information on the specific dates and locations of political violence, the types of event, the groups involved, fatalities and changes in territorial control. Information is recorded on the battles, killings, riots, and recruitment activities of rebels, governments, militias, armed groups, protesters and civilians. \\r\\n\\r\\nAs of early 2015, ACLED has recorded over 100,000 individual events, with ongoing data collection focused on Africa, South Asia and South East Asia. Data can be used for medium- and long-term analysis and mapping of political violence across developing countries through use of historical data from 1997, as well as informing humanitarian and development work in crisis and conflict-affected contexts through realtime data updates and reports. Despite the waning of civil wars across the developing world, ACLED data show that political violence rates have remained relatively stable in the past eighteen years. ACLED does not have a fatality threshold for event inclusion. This means that conflict and demonstration events in ACLED do not have to produce any fatalities in order to be included as a valid event. We use no arbitrary number of deaths to define a conflict.\\n2. ACLED reports fatalities only when a reputable source has relayed that information. Further, researchers seek out information to triangulate – where and when possible – the numbers from any report.\\n3. ACLED uses the most conservative estimate available, and will revise and correct the totals – upward or downward – when better information comes available.\\n\\nACLED advises caution in using all fatality numbers from its, or any other conflict data source. Fatality information is the most biased, and least accurate, part of any conflict report and extreme caution should be employed when using any fatality number to show patterns.',\n     metadata_modified: '2018-11-17T01:17:29.806112',\n     author: null,\n     author_email: null,\n     subnational: '1',\n     state: 'active',\n     has_geodata: false,\n     methodology: 'Other',\n     version: null,\n     is_requestdata_type: false,\n     license_id: 'cc-by-sa',\n     num_of_showcases: 1,\n     type: 'dataset',\n     resources: [ [Object] ],\n     dataset_preview: 'first_resource',\n     num_resources: 1,\n     dataset_source: 'ACLED',\n     tags: [ [Object], [Object], [Object], [Object] ],\n     revision_id: '0758c9d3-415a-4cc5-af2c-4489be86d1a6',\n     groups: [ [Object] ],\n     creator_user_id: '154de241-38d6-47d3-a77f-0a9848a61df3',\n     has_quickcharts: true,\n     methodology_other: '[ACLED\\'s Methodology page](https://www.acleddata.com/resources/methodology/) contains information about how the ACLED team collects, cleans, reviews and checks event data, with a focus on what makes ACLED unique and compatible with other data. The process of ACLED coding assures that it is accurate, comprehensive, transparent and regularly updated. Data are posted as they are complete, although there are ongoing checks to ensure the thoroughness of previously collected events.',\n     relationships_as_subject: [],\n     total_res_downloads: 7,\n     organization: \n      { description: 'ACLED (Armed Conflict Location & Event Data Project) is the most comprehensive public collection of political violence data for developing states. This dataset contains information on the specific dates and locations of political violence, the types of event, the groups involved, fatalities and changes in territorial control. Information is recorded on the battles, killings, riots, and recruitment activities of rebels, governments, militias, armed groups, protesters and civilians. \\r\\n\\r\\nAs of early 2015, ACLED has recorded over 100,000 individual events, with ongoing data collection focused on Africa, South Asia and South East Asia. Data can be used for medium- and long-term analysis and mapping of political violence across developing countries through use of historical data from 1997, as well as informing humanitarian and development work in crisis and conflict-affected contexts through realtime data updates and reports. Despite the waning of civil wars across the developing world, ACLED data show that political violence rates have remained relatively stable in the past eighteen years. ACLED seeks to support research and work devoted to understanding, predicting and reducing levels of violence and their consequences.',\n        created: '2015-01-09T14:44:54.006612',\n        title: 'Armed Conflict Location & Event Data Project (ACLED)',\n        name: 'acled',\n        is_organization: true,\n        state: 'active',\n        image_url: '',\n        revision_id: 'ca4f1ccc-0a39-4785-af1d-f7257d504829',\n        type: 'organization',\n        id: 'b67e6c74-c185-4f43-b561-0e114a736f19',\n        approval_status: 'approved' },\n     name: 'acled-data-for-gambia',\n     isopen: true,\n     url: null,\n     notes: 'The ACLED project codes reported information on the type, agents, exact location, date, and other characteristics of political violence events, demonstrations and select politically relevant non-violent events. ACLED does not have a fatality threshold for event inclusion. This means that conflict and demonstration events in ACLED do not have to produce any fatalities in order to be included as a valid event. We use no arbitrary number of deaths to define a conflict.\\n2. ACLED reports fatalities only when a reputable source has relayed that information. Further, researchers seek out information to triangulate – where and when possible – the numbers from any report.\\n3. ACLED uses the most conservative estimate available, and will revise and correct the totals – upward or downward – when better information comes available.\\n\\nACLED advises caution in using all fatality numbers from its, or any other conflict data source. Information is recorded on the battles, killings, riots, and recruitment activities of rebels, governments, militias, armed groups, protesters and civilians. \\r\\n\\r\\nAs of early 2015, ACLED has recorded over 100,000 individual events, with ongoing data collection focused on Africa, South Asia and South East Asia. Data can be used for medium- and long-term analysis and mapping of political violence across developing countries through use of historical data from 1997, as well as informing humanitarian and development work in crisis and conflict-affected contexts through realtime data updates and reports. Despite the waning of civil wars across the developing world, ACLED data show that political violence rates have remained relatively stable in the past eighteen years. ACLED does not have a fatality threshold for event inclusion. This means that conflict and demonstration events in ACLED do not have to produce any fatalities in order to be included as a valid event. We use no arbitrary number of deaths to define a conflict.\\n2. ACLED reports fatalities only when a reputable source has relayed that information. Further, researchers seek out information to triangulate – where and when possible – the numbers from any report.\\n3. ACLED uses the most conservative estimate available, and will revise and correct the totals – upward or downward – when better information comes available.\\n\\nACLED advises caution in using all fatality numbers from its, or any other conflict data source. Fatality information is the most biased, and least accurate, part of any conflict report and extreme caution should be employed when using any fatality number to show patterns.',\n     metadata_modified: '2018-11-17T01:16:14.677564',\n     author: null,\n     author_email: null,\n     subnational: '1',\n     state: 'active',\n     has_geodata: false,\n     methodology: 'Other',\n     version: null,\n     is_requestdata_type: false,\n     license_id: 'cc-by-sa',\n     num_of_showcases: 1,\n     type: 'dataset',\n     resources: [ [Object] ],\n     dataset_preview: 'first_resource',\n     num_resources: 1,\n     dataset_source: 'ACLED',\n     tags: [ [Object], [Object], [Object], [Object] ],\n     revision_id: '66e4db99-9c18-439f-88e6-e02ac901e544',\n     groups: [ [Object] ],\n     creator_user_id: '154de241-38d6-47d3-a77f-0a9848a61df3',\n     has_quickcharts: true,\n     methodology_other: '[ACLED\\'s Methodology page](https://www.acleddata.com/resources/methodology/) contains information about how the ACLED team collects, cleans, reviews and checks event data, with a focus on what makes ACLED unique and compatible with other data. This dataset contains information on the specific dates and locations of political violence, the types of event, the groups involved, fatalities and changes in territorial control. Information is recorded on the battles, killings, riots, and recruitment activities of rebels, governments, militias, armed groups, protesters and civilians. \\r\\n\\r\\nAs of early 2015, ACLED has recorded over 100,000 individual events, with ongoing data collection focused on Africa, South Asia and South East Asia. Data can be used for medium- and long-term analysis and mapping of political violence across developing countries through use of historical data from 1997, as well as informing humanitarian and development work in crisis and conflict-affected contexts through realtime data updates and reports. Despite the waning of civil wars across the developing world, ACLED data show that political violence rates have remained relatively stable in the past eighteen years. ACLED does not have a fatality threshold for event inclusion. This means that conflict and demonstration events in ACLED do not have to produce any fatalities in order to be included as a valid event. We use no arbitrary number of deaths to define a conflict.\\n2. ACLED reports fatalities only when a reputable source has relayed that information. Further, researchers seek out information to triangulate – where and when possible – the numbers from any report.\\n3. ACLED uses the most conservative estimate available, and will revise and correct the totals – upward or downward – when better information comes available.\\n\\nACLED advises caution in using all fatality numbers from its, or any other conflict data source. ACLED does not have a fatality threshold for event inclusion. This means that conflict and demonstration events in ACLED do not have to produce any fatalities in order to be included as a valid event. We use no arbitrary number of deaths to define a conflict.\\n2. ACLED reports fatalities only when a reputable source has relayed that information. Further, researchers seek out information to triangulate – where and when possible – the numbers from any report.\\n3. ACLED uses the most conservative estimate available, and will revise and correct the totals – upward or downward – when better information comes available.\\n\\nACLED advises caution in using all fatality numbers from its, or any other conflict data source. Fatality information is the most biased, and least accurate, part of any conflict report and extreme caution should be employed when using any fatality number to show patterns.',\n     metadata_modified: '2018-11-17T01:16:02.193078',\n     author: null,\n     author_email: null,\n     subnational: '1',\n     state: 'active',\n     has_geodata: false,\n     methodology: 'Other',\n     version: null,\n     is_requestdata_type: false,\n     license_id: 'cc-by-sa',\n     num_of_showcases: 1,\n     type: 'dataset',\n     resources: [ [Object] ],\n     dataset_preview: 'first_resource',\n     num_resources: 1,\n     dataset_source: 'ACLED',\n     tags: [ [Object], [Object], [Object], [Object] ],\n     revision_id: '31328bf1-a408-4df6-b10f-3261e4efc591',\n     groups: [ [Object] ],\n     creator_user_id: '154de241-38d6-47d3-a77f-0a9848a61df3',\n     has_quickcharts: true,\n     methodology_other: '[ACLED\\'s Methodology page](https://www.acleddata.com/resources/methodology/) contains information about how the ACLED team collects, cleans, reviews and checks event data, with a focus on what makes ACLED unique and compatible with other data. This dataset contains information on the specific dates and locations of political violence, the types of event, the groups involved, fatalities and changes in territorial control. Information is recorded on the battles, killings, riots, and recruitment activities of rebels, governments, militias, armed groups, protesters and civilians. \\r\\n\\r\\nAs of early 2015, ACLED has recorded over 100,000 individual events, with ongoing data collection focused on Africa, South Asia and South East Asia. Data can be used for medium- and long-term analysis and mapping of political violence across developing countries through use of historical data from 1997, as well as informing humanitarian and development work in crisis and conflict-affected contexts through realtime data updates and reports. Despite the waning of civil wars across the developing world, ACLED data show that political violence rates have remained relatively stable in the past eighteen years. ACLED does not have a fatality threshold for event inclusion. This means that conflict and demonstration events in ACLED do not have to produce any fatalities in order to be included as a valid event. We use no arbitrary number of deaths to define a conflict.\\n2. ACLED reports fatalities only when a reputable source has relayed that information. Further, researchers seek out information to triangulate – where and when possible – the numbers from any report.\\n3. ACLED uses the most conservative estimate available, and will revise and correct the totals – upward or downward – when better information comes available.\\n\\nACLED advises caution in using all fatality numbers from its, or any other conflict data source. Data can be used for medium- and long-term analysis and mapping of political violence across developing countries through use of historical data from 1997, as well as informing humanitarian and development work in crisis and conflict-affected contexts through realtime data updates and reports. ACLED does not have a fatality threshold for event inclusion. This means that conflict and demonstration events in ACLED do not have to produce any fatalities in order to be included as a valid event. We use no arbitrary number of deaths to define a conflict.\\n2. ACLED reports fatalities only when a reputable source has relayed that information. Further, researchers seek out information to triangulate – where and when possible – the numbers from any report.\\n3. ACLED uses the most conservative estimate available, and will revise and correct the totals – upward or downward – when better information comes available.\\n\\nACLED advises caution in using all fatality numbers from its, or any other conflict data source. ACLED does not have a fatality threshold for event inclusion. This means that conflict and demonstration events in ACLED do not have to produce any fatalities in order to be included as a valid event. We use no arbitrary number of deaths to define a conflict.\\n2. ACLED reports fatalities only when a reputable source has relayed that information. Further, researchers seek out information to triangulate – where and when possible – the numbers from any report.\\n3. ACLED uses the most conservative estimate available, and will revise and correct the totals – upward or downward – when better information comes available.\\n\\nACLED advises caution in using all fatality numbers from its, or any other conflict data source. Fatality information is the most biased, and least accurate, part of any conflict report and extreme caution should be employed when using any fatality number to show patterns.',\n     metadata_modified: '2018-11-17T01:15:38.381426',\n     author: null,\n     author_email: null,\n     subnational: '1',\n     state: 'active',\n     has_geodata: false,\n     methodology: 'Other',\n     version: null,\n     is_requestdata_type: false,\n     license_id: 'cc-by-sa',\n     num_of_showcases: 1,\n     type: 'dataset',\n     resources: [ [Object] ],\n     dataset_preview: 'first_resource',\n     num_resources: 1,\n     dataset_source: 'ACLED',\n     tags: [ [Object], [Object], [Object], [Object] ],\n     revision_id: '1cca040a-db12-42d1-88fa-edb529878bed',\n     groups: [ [Object] ],\n     creator_user_id: '154de241-38d6-47d3-a77f-0a9848a61df3',\n     has_quickcharts: true,\n     methodology_other: '[ACLED\\'s Methodology page](https://www.acleddata.com/resources/methodology/) contains information about how the ACLED team collects, cleans, reviews and checks event data, with a focus on what makes ACLED unique and compatible with other data. This dataset contains information on the specific dates and locations of political violence, the types of event, the groups involved, fatalities and changes in territorial control. Information is recorded on the battles, killings, riots, and recruitment activities of rebels, governments, militias, armed groups, protesters and civilians. \\r\\n\\r\\nAs of early 2015, ACLED has recorded over 100,000 individual events, with ongoing data collection focused on Africa, South Asia and South East Asia. Data can be used for medium- and long-term analysis and mapping of political violence across developing countries through use of historical data from 1997, as well as informing humanitarian and development work in crisis and conflict-affected contexts through realtime data updates and reports. Despite the waning of civil wars across the developing world, ACLED data show that political violence rates have remained relatively stable in the past eighteen years. ACLED seeks to support research and work devoted to understanding, predicting and reducing levels of violence and their consequences.',\n        created: '2015-01-09T14:44:54.006612',\n        title: 'Armed Conflict Location & Event Data Project (ACLED)',\n        name: 'acled',\n        is_organization: true,\n        state: 'active',\n        image_url: '',\n        revision_id: 'ca4f1ccc-0a39-4785-af1d-f7257d504829',\n        type: 'organization',\n        id: 'b67e6c74-c185-4f43-b561-0e114a736f19',\n        approval_status: 'approved' },\n     name: 'acled-data-for-israel',\n     isopen: true,\n     url: null,\n     notes: 'The ACLED project codes reported information on the type, agents, exact location, date, and other characteristics of political violence events, demonstrations and select politically relevant non-violent events. ACLED does not have a fatality threshold for event inclusion. This means that conflict and demonstration events in ACLED do not have to produce any fatalities in order to be included as a valid event. We use no arbitrary number of deaths to define a conflict.\\n2. ACLED reports fatalities only when a reputable source has relayed that information. Further, researchers seek out information to triangulate – where and when possible – the numbers from any report.\\n3. ACLED uses the most conservative estimate available, and will revise and correct the totals – upward or downward – when better information comes available.\\n\\nACLED advises caution in using all fatality numbers from its, or any other conflict data source. Fatality information is the most biased, and least accurate, part of any conflict report and extreme caution should be employed when using any fatality number to show patterns.',\n     metadata_modified: '2018-11-17T01:16:09.295121',\n     author: null,\n     author_email: null,\n     subnational: '1',\n     state: 'active',\n     has_geodata: false,\n     methodology: 'Other',\n     version: null,\n     is_requestdata_type: false,\n     license_id: 'cc-by-sa',\n     num_of_showcases: 1,\n     type: 'dataset',\n     resources: [ [Object] ],\n     dataset_preview: 'first_resource',\n     num_resources: 1,\n     dataset_source: 'ACLED',\n     tags: [ [Object], [Object], [Object], [Object] ],\n     revision_id: '5f32787f-8c2f-4f4a-85bb-a2c6b05304e4',\n     groups: [ [Object] ],\n     creator_user_id: '154de241-38d6-47d3-a77f-0a9848a61df3',\n     has_quickcharts: true,\n     methodology_other: '[ACLED\\'s Methodology page](https://www.acleddata.com/resources/methodology/) contains information about how the ACLED team collects, cleans, reviews and checks event data, with a focus on what makes ACLED unique and compatible with other data. Information is recorded on the battles, killings, riots, and recruitment activities of rebels, governments, militias, armed groups, protesters and civilians. \\r\\n\\r\\nAs of early 2015, ACLED has recorded over 100,000 individual events, with ongoing data collection focused on Africa, South Asia and South East Asia. Data can be used for medium- and long-term analysis and mapping of political violence across developing countries through use of historical data from 1997, as well as informing humanitarian and development work in crisis and conflict-affected contexts through realtime data updates and reports. Despite the waning of civil wars across the developing world, ACLED data show that political violence rates have remained relatively stable in the past eighteen years. ACLED does not have a fatality threshold for event inclusion. This means that conflict and demonstration events in ACLED do not have to produce any fatalities in order to be included as a valid event. We use no arbitrary number of deaths to define a conflict.\\n2. ACLED reports fatalities only when a reputable source has relayed that information. Further, researchers seek out information to triangulate – where and when possible – the numbers from any report.\\n3. ACLED uses the most conservative estimate available, and will revise and correct the totals – upward or downward – when better information comes available.\\n\\nACLED advises caution in using all fatality numbers from its, or any other conflict data source. Fatality information is the most biased, and least accurate, part of any conflict report and extreme caution should be employed when using any fatality number to show patterns.',\n     metadata_modified: '2018-11-17T01:16:28.792692',\n     author: null,\n     author_email: null,\n     subnational: '1',\n     state: 'active',\n     has_geodata: false,\n     methodology: 'Other',\n     version: null,\n     is_requestdata_type: false,\n     license_id: 'cc-by-sa',\n     num_of_showcases: 1,\n     type: 'dataset',\n     resources: [ [Object] ],\n     dataset_preview: 'first_resource',\n     num_resources: 1,\n     dataset_source: 'ACLED',\n     tags: [ [Object], [Object], [Object], [Object] ],\n     revision_id: '06897c8b-bd28-4309-92c3-aa93bfc83601',\n     groups: [ [Object] ],\n     creator_user_id: '154de241-38d6-47d3-a77f-0a9848a61df3',\n     has_quickcharts: true,\n     methodology_other: '[ACLED\\'s Methodology page](https://www.acleddata.com/resources/methodology/) contains information about how the ACLED team collects, cleans, reviews and checks event data, with a focus on what makes ACLED unique and compatible with other data. This dataset contains information on the specific dates and locations of political violence, the types of event, the groups involved, fatalities and changes in territorial control. Information is recorded on the battles, killings, riots, and recruitment activities of rebels, governments, militias, armed groups, protesters and civilians. \\r\\n\\r\\nAs of early 2015, ACLED has recorded over 100,000 individual events, with ongoing data collection focused on Africa, South Asia and South East Asia. Data can be used for medium- and long-term analysis and mapping of political violence across developing countries through use of historical data from 1997, as well as informing humanitarian and development work in crisis and conflict-affected contexts through realtime data updates and reports. Despite the waning of civil wars across the developing world, ACLED data show that political violence rates have remained relatively stable in the past eighteen years. ACLED seeks to support research and work devoted to understanding, predicting and reducing levels of violence and their consequences.',\n        created: '2015-01-09T14:44:54.006612',\n        title: 'Armed Conflict Location & Event Data Project (ACLED)',\n        name: 'acled',\n        is_organization: true,\n        state: 'active',\n        image_url: '',\n        revision_id: 'ca4f1ccc-0a39-4785-af1d-f7257d504829',\n        type: 'organization',\n        id: 'b67e6c74-c185-4f43-b561-0e114a736f19',\n        approval_status: 'approved' },\n     name: 'acled-data-for-kenya',\n     isopen: true,\n     url: null,\n     notes: 'The ACLED project codes reported information on the type, agents, exact location, date, and other characteristics of political violence events, demonstrations and select politically relevant non-violent events. ACLED does not have a fatality threshold for event inclusion. This means that conflict and demonstration events in ACLED do not have to produce any fatalities in order to be included as a valid event. We use no arbitrary number of deaths to define a conflict.\\n2. ACLED reports fatalities only when a reputable source has relayed that information. Further, researchers seek out information to triangulate – where and when possible – the numbers from any report.\\n3. ACLED uses the most conservative estimate available, and will revise and correct the totals – upward or downward – when better information comes available.\\n\\nACLED advises caution in using all fatality numbers from its, or any other conflict data source. Fatality information is the most biased, and least accurate, part of any conflict report and extreme caution should be employed when using any fatality number to show patterns.',\n     metadata_modified: '2018-09-16T00:31:30.493428',\n     author: null,\n     author_email: null,\n     subnational: '1',\n     state: 'active',\n     has_geodata: false,\n     methodology: 'Other',\n     version: null,\n     is_requestdata_type: false,\n     license_id: 'cc-by-sa',\n     num_of_showcases: 1,\n     type: 'dataset',\n     resources: [ [Object] ],\n     dataset_preview: 'first_resource',\n     num_resources: 1,\n     dataset_source: 'ACLED',\n     tags: [ [Object], [Object], [Object], [Object] ],\n     revision_id: '9b850411-0855-4aba-84f5-9e6b56acd962',\n     groups: [ [Object] ],\n     creator_user_id: '154de241-38d6-47d3-a77f-0a9848a61df3',\n     has_quickcharts: true,\n     methodology_other: '[ACLED\\'s Methodology page](https://www.acleddata.com/resources/methodology/) contains information about how the ACLED team collects, cleans, reviews and checks event data, with a focus on what makes ACLED unique and compatible with other data. Information is recorded on the battles, killings, riots, and recruitment activities of rebels, governments, militias, armed groups, protesters and civilians. \\r\\n\\r\\nAs of early 2015, ACLED has recorded over 100,000 individual events, with ongoing data collection focused on Africa, South Asia and South East Asia. Data can be used for medium- and long-term analysis and mapping of political violence across developing countries through use of historical data from 1997, as well as informing humanitarian and development work in crisis and conflict-affected contexts through realtime data updates and reports. Despite the waning of civil wars across the developing world, ACLED data show that political violence rates have remained relatively stable in the past eighteen years. ACLED does not have a fatality threshold for event inclusion. This means that conflict and demonstration events in ACLED do not have to produce any fatalities in order to be included as a valid event. We use no arbitrary number of deaths to define a conflict.\\n2. ACLED reports fatalities only when a reputable source has relayed that information. Further, researchers seek out information to triangulate – where and when possible – the numbers from any report.\\n3. ACLED uses the most conservative estimate available, and will revise and correct the totals – upward or downward – when better information comes available.\\n\\nACLED advises caution in using all fatality numbers from its, or any other conflict data source. Fatality information is the most biased, and least accurate, part of any conflict report and extreme caution should be employed when using any fatality number to show patterns.',\n     metadata_modified: '2018-08-16T01:49:36.594145',\n     author: null,\n     author_email: null,\n     subnational: '1',\n     state: 'active',\n     has_geodata: false,\n     methodology: 'Other',\n     version: null,\n     is_requestdata_type: false,\n     license_id: 'cc-by-sa',\n     num_of_showcases: 1,\n     type: 'dataset',\n     resources: [ [Object] ],\n     dataset_preview: 'first_resource',\n     num_resources: 1,\n     dataset_source: 'ACLED',\n     tags: [ [Object], [Object], [Object], [Object] ],\n     revision_id: '9a728350-30ca-4a83-aa6e-eed5cb4a7010',\n     groups: [ [Object] ],\n     creator_user_id: '154de241-38d6-47d3-a77f-0a9848a61df3',\n     has_quickcharts: true,\n     methodology_other: '[ACLED\\'s Methodology page](https://www.acleddata.com/resources/methodology/) contains information about how the ACLED team collects, cleans, reviews and checks event data, with a focus on what makes ACLED unique and compatible with other data. Information is recorded on the battles, killings, riots, and recruitment activities of rebels, governments, militias, armed groups, protesters and civilians. \\r\\n\\r\\nAs of early 2015, ACLED has recorded over 100,000 individual events, with ongoing data collection focused on Africa, South Asia and South East Asia. Data can be used for medium- and long-term analysis and mapping of political violence across developing countries through use of historical data from 1997, as well as informing humanitarian and development work in crisis and conflict-affected contexts through realtime data updates and reports. Despite the waning of civil wars across the developing world, ACLED data show that political violence rates have remained relatively stable in the past eighteen years. ACLED does not have a fatality threshold for event inclusion. This means that conflict and demonstration events in ACLED do not have to produce any fatalities in order to be included as a valid event. We use no arbitrary number of deaths to define a conflict.\\n2. ACLED reports fatalities only when a reputable source has relayed that information. Further, researchers seek out information to triangulate – where and when possible – the numbers from any report.\\n3. ACLED uses the most conservative estimate available, and will revise and correct the totals – upward or downward – when better information comes available.\\n\\nACLED advises caution in using all fatality numbers from its, or any other conflict data source. Fatality information is the most biased, and least accurate, part of any conflict report and extreme caution should be employed when using any fatality number to show patterns.',\n     metadata_modified: '2018-11-17T01:15:35.324844',\n     author: null,\n     author_email: null,\n     subnational: '1',\n     state: 'active',\n     has_geodata: false,\n     methodology: 'Other',\n     version: null,\n     is_requestdata_type: false,\n     license_id: 'cc-by-sa',\n     num_of_showcases: 1,\n     type: 'dataset',\n     resources: [ [Object] ],\n     dataset_preview: 'first_resource',\n     num_resources: 1,\n     dataset_source: 'ACLED',\n     tags: [ [Object], [Object], [Object], [Object] ],\n     revision_id: 'c78d4238-a35a-4674-8060-5a596a9f0627',\n     groups: [ [Object] ],\n     creator_user_id: '154de241-38d6-47d3-a77f-0a9848a61df3',\n     has_quickcharts: true,\n     methodology_other: '[ACLED\\'s Methodology page](https://www.acleddata.com/resources/methodology/) contains information about how the ACLED team collects, cleans, reviews and checks event data, with a focus on what makes ACLED unique and compatible with other data. This dataset contains information on the specific dates and locations of political violence, the types of event, the groups involved, fatalities and changes in territorial control. Information is recorded on the battles, killings, riots, and recruitment activities of rebels, governments, militias, armed groups, protesters and civilians. \\r\\n\\r\\nAs of early 2015, ACLED has recorded over 100,000 individual events, with ongoing data collection focused on Africa, South Asia and South East Asia. Data can be used for medium- and long-term analysis and mapping of political violence across developing countries through use of historical data from 1997, as well as informing humanitarian and development work in crisis and conflict-affected contexts through realtime data updates and reports. Despite the waning of civil wars across the developing world, ACLED data show that political violence rates have remained relatively stable in the past eighteen years. ACLED seeks to support research and work devoted to understanding, predicting and reducing levels of violence and their consequences.',\n        created: '2015-01-09T14:44:54.006612',\n        title: 'Armed Conflict Location & Event Data Project (ACLED)',\n        name: 'acled',\n        is_organization: true,\n        state: 'active',\n        image_url: '',\n        revision_id: 'ca4f1ccc-0a39-4785-af1d-f7257d504829',\n        type: 'organization',\n        id: 'b67e6c74-c185-4f43-b561-0e114a736f19',\n        approval_status: 'approved' },\n     name: 'acled-data-for-lebanon',\n     isopen: true,\n     url: null,\n     notes: 'The ACLED project codes reported information on the type, agents, exact location, date, and other characteristics of political violence events, demonstrations and select politically relevant non-violent events. ACLED does not have a fatality threshold for event inclusion. This means that conflict and demonstration events in ACLED do not have to produce any fatalities in order to be included as a valid event. We use no arbitrary number of deaths to define a conflict.\\n2. ACLED reports fatalities only when a reputable source has relayed that information. Further, researchers seek out information to triangulate – where and when possible – the numbers from any report.\\n3. ACLED uses the most conservative estimate available, and will revise and correct the totals – upward or downward – when better information comes available.\\n\\nACLED advises caution in using all fatality numbers from its, or any other conflict data source. ACLED does not have a fatality threshold for event inclusion. This means that conflict and demonstration events in ACLED do not have to produce any fatalities in order to be included as a valid event. We use no arbitrary number of deaths to define a conflict.\\n2. ACLED reports fatalities only when a reputable source has relayed that information. Further, researchers seek out information to triangulate – where and when possible – the numbers from any report.\\n3. ACLED uses the most conservative estimate available, and will revise and correct the totals – upward or downward – when better information comes available.\\n\\nACLED advises caution in using all fatality numbers from its, or any other conflict data source. Information is recorded on the battles, killings, riots, and recruitment activities of rebels, governments, militias, armed groups, protesters and civilians. \\r\\n\\r\\nAs of early 2015, ACLED has recorded over 100,000 individual events, with ongoing data collection focused on Africa, South Asia and South East Asia. Data can be used for medium- and long-term analysis and mapping of political violence across developing countries through use of historical data from 1997, as well as informing humanitarian and development work in crisis and conflict-affected contexts through realtime data updates and reports. Despite the waning of civil wars across the developing world, ACLED data show that political violence rates have remained relatively stable in the past eighteen years. ACLED does not have a fatality threshold for event inclusion. This means that conflict and demonstration events in ACLED do not have to produce any fatalities in order to be included as a valid event. We use no arbitrary number of deaths to define a conflict.\\n2. ACLED reports fatalities only when a reputable source has relayed that information. Further, researchers seek out information to triangulate – where and when possible – the numbers from any report.\\n3. ACLED uses the most conservative estimate available, and will revise and correct the totals – upward or downward – when better information comes available.\\n\\nACLED advises caution in using all fatality numbers from its, or any other conflict data source. Fatality information is the most biased, and least accurate, part of any conflict report and extreme caution should be employed when using any fatality number to show patterns.',\n     metadata_modified: '2018-11-17T01:16:25.994413',\n     author: null,\n     author_email: null,\n     subnational: '1',\n     state: 'active',\n     has_geodata: false,\n     methodology: 'Other',\n     version: null,\n     is_requestdata_type: false,\n     license_id: 'cc-by-sa',\n     num_of_showcases: 1,\n     type: 'dataset',\n     resources: [ [Object] ],\n     dataset_preview: 'first_resource',\n     num_resources: 1,\n     dataset_source: 'ACLED',\n     tags: [ [Object], [Object], [Object], [Object] ],\n     revision_id: '84782be7-e6e4-40fb-8cdf-fda238482a06',\n     groups: [ [Object] ],\n     creator_user_id: '154de241-38d6-47d3-a77f-0a9848a61df3',\n     has_quickcharts: true,\n     methodology_other: '[ACLED\\'s Methodology page](https://www.acleddata.com/resources/methodology/) contains information about how the ACLED team collects, cleans, reviews and checks event data, with a focus on what makes ACLED unique and compatible with other data. This dataset contains information on the specific dates and locations of political violence, the types of event, the groups involved, fatalities and changes in territorial control. Information is recorded on the battles, killings, riots, and recruitment activities of rebels, governments, militias, armed groups, protesters and civilians. \\r\\n\\r\\nAs of early 2015, ACLED has recorded over 100,000 individual events, with ongoing data collection focused on Africa, South Asia and South East Asia. Data can be used for medium- and long-term analysis and mapping of political violence across developing countries through use of historical data from 1997, as well as informing humanitarian and development work in crisis and conflict-affected contexts through realtime data updates and reports. Despite the waning of civil wars across the developing world, ACLED data show that political violence rates have remained relatively stable in the past eighteen years. ACLED does not have a fatality threshold for event inclusion. This means that conflict and demonstration events in ACLED do not have to produce any fatalities in order to be included as a valid event. We use no arbitrary number of deaths to define a conflict.\\n2. ACLED reports fatalities only when a reputable source has relayed that information. Further, researchers seek out information to triangulate – where and when possible – the numbers from any report.\\n3. ACLED uses the most conservative estimate available, and will revise and correct the totals – upward or downward – when better information comes available.\\n\\nACLED advises caution in using all fatality numbers from its, or any other conflict data source. Fatality information is the most biased, and least accurate, part of any conflict report and extreme caution should be employed when using any fatality number to show patterns.',\n     metadata_modified: '2018-11-17T01:16:06.489589',\n     author: null,\n     author_email: null,\n     subnational: '1',\n     state: 'active',\n     has_geodata: false,\n     methodology: 'Other',\n     version: null,\n     is_requestdata_type: false,\n     license_id: 'cc-by-sa',\n     num_of_showcases: 1,\n     type: 'dataset',\n     resources: [ [Object] ],\n     dataset_preview: 'first_resource',\n     num_resources: 1,\n     dataset_source: 'ACLED',\n     tags: [ [Object], [Object], [Object], [Object] ],\n     revision_id: 'bcbb7755-c718-4de7-9401-a0ca2347209a',\n     groups: [ [Object] ],\n     creator_user_id: '154de241-38d6-47d3-a77f-0a9848a61df3',\n     has_quickcharts: true,\n     methodology_other: '[ACLED\\'s Methodology page](https://www.acleddata.com/resources/methodology/) contains information about how the ACLED team collects, cleans, reviews and checks event data, with a focus on what makes ACLED unique and compatible with other data. This dataset contains information on the specific dates and locations of political violence, the types of event, the groups involved, fatalities and changes in territorial control. Information is recorded on the battles, killings, riots, and recruitment activities of rebels, governments, militias, armed groups, protesters and civilians. \\r\\n\\r\\nAs of early 2015, ACLED has recorded over 100,000 individual events, with ongoing data collection focused on Africa, South Asia and South East Asia. Data can be used for medium- and long-term analysis and mapping of political violence across developing countries through use of historical data from 1997, as well as informing humanitarian and development work in crisis and conflict-affected contexts through realtime data updates and reports. Despite the waning of civil wars across the developing world, ACLED data show that political violence rates have remained relatively stable in the past eighteen years. ACLED does not have a fatality threshold for event inclusion. This means that conflict and demonstration events in ACLED do not have to produce any fatalities in order to be included as a valid event. We use no arbitrary number of deaths to define a conflict.\\n2. ACLED reports fatalities only when a reputable source has relayed that information. Further, researchers seek out information to triangulate – where and when possible – the numbers from any report.\\n3. ACLED uses the most conservative estimate available, and will revise and correct the totals – upward or downward – when better information comes available.\\n\\nACLED advises caution in using all fatality numbers from its, or any other conflict data source. Fatality information is the most biased, and least accurate, part of any conflict report and extreme caution should be employed when using any fatality number to show patterns.',\n     metadata_modified: '2018-11-17T01:16:52.574327',\n     author: null,\n     author_email: null,\n     subnational: '1',\n     state: 'active',\n     has_geodata: false,\n     methodology: 'Other',\n     version: null,\n     is_requestdata_type: false,\n     license_id: 'cc-by-sa',\n     num_of_showcases: 1,\n     type: 'dataset',\n     resources: [ [Object] ],\n     dataset_preview: 'first_resource',\n     num_resources: 1,\n     dataset_source: 'ACLED',\n     tags: [ [Object], [Object], [Object], [Object] ],\n     revision_id: '49ac0703-771d-4f88-a745-50886d4d9de3',\n     groups: [ [Object] ],\n     creator_user_id: '154de241-38d6-47d3-a77f-0a9848a61df3',\n     has_quickcharts: true,\n     methodology_other: '[ACLED\\'s Methodology page](https://www.acleddata.com/resources/methodology/) contains information about how the ACLED team collects, cleans, reviews and checks event data, with a focus on what makes ACLED unique and compatible with other data. Data are posted as they are complete, although there are ongoing checks to ensure the thoroughness of previously collected events.',\n     relationships_as_subject: [],\n     total_res_downloads: 4,\n     organization: \n      { description: 'ACLED (Armed Conflict Location & Event Data Project) is the most comprehensive public collection of political violence data for developing states. This dataset contains information on the specific dates and locations of political violence, the types of event, the groups involved, fatalities and changes in territorial control. Information is recorded on the battles, killings, riots, and recruitment activities of rebels, governments, militias, armed groups, protesters and civilians. \\r\\n\\r\\nAs of early 2015, ACLED has recorded over 100,000 individual events, with ongoing data collection focused on Africa, South Asia and South East Asia. Data can be used for medium- and long-term analysis and mapping of political violence across developing countries through use of historical data from 1997, as well as informing humanitarian and development work in crisis and conflict-affected contexts through realtime data updates and reports. Despite the waning of civil wars across the developing world, ACLED data show that political violence rates have remained relatively stable in the past eighteen years. ACLED seeks to support research and work devoted to understanding, predicting and reducing levels of violence and their consequences.',\n        created: '2015-01-09T14:44:54.006612',\n        title: 'Armed Conflict Location & Event Data Project (ACLED)',\n        name: 'acled',\n        is_organization: true,\n        state: 'active',\n        image_url: '',\n        revision_id: 'ca4f1ccc-0a39-4785-af1d-f7257d504829',\n        type: 'organization',\n        id: 'b67e6c74-c185-4f43-b561-0e114a736f19',\n        approval_status: 'approved' },\n     name: 'acled-data-for-malawi',\n     isopen: true,\n     url: null,\n     notes: 'The ACLED project codes reported information on the type, agents, exact location, date, and other characteristics of political violence events, demonstrations and select politically relevant non-violent events. ACLED does not have a fatality threshold for event inclusion. This means that conflict and demonstration events in ACLED do not have to produce any fatalities in order to be included as a valid event. We use no arbitrary number of deaths to define a conflict.\\n2. ACLED reports fatalities only when a reputable source has relayed that information. Further, researchers seek out information to triangulate – where and when possible – the numbers from any report.\\n3. ACLED uses the most conservative estimate available, and will revise and correct the totals – upward or downward – when better information comes available.\\n\\nACLED advises caution in using all fatality numbers from its, or any other conflict data source. Data can be used for medium- and long-term analysis and mapping of political violence across developing countries through use of historical data from 1997, as well as informing humanitarian and development work in crisis and conflict-affected contexts through realtime data updates and reports. The southern Africa region has fewer protracted humanitarian crises, but is prone to drought and floods. For this reason, OCHA does not have country offices in the region. ACLED does not have a fatality threshold for event inclusion. This means that conflict and demonstration events in ACLED do not have to produce any fatalities in order to be included as a valid event. We use no arbitrary number of deaths to define a conflict.\\n2. ACLED reports fatalities only when a reputable source has relayed that information. Further, researchers seek out information to triangulate – where and when possible – the numbers from any report.\\n3. ACLED uses the most conservative estimate available, and will revise and correct the totals – upward or downward – when better information comes available.\\n\\nACLED advises caution in using all fatality numbers from its, or any other conflict data source. ACLED does not have a fatality threshold for event inclusion. This means that conflict and demonstration events in ACLED do not have to produce any fatalities in order to be included as a valid event. We use no arbitrary number of deaths to define a conflict.\\n2. ACLED reports fatalities only when a reputable source has relayed that information. Further, researchers seek out information to triangulate – where and when possible – the numbers from any report.\\n3. ACLED uses the most conservative estimate available, and will revise and correct the totals – upward or downward – when better information comes available.\\n\\nACLED advises caution in using all fatality numbers from its, or any other conflict data source. Fatality information is the most biased, and least accurate, part of any conflict report and extreme caution should be employed when using any fatality number to show patterns.',\n     metadata_modified: '2018-11-17T01:16:30.291027',\n     author: null,\n     author_email: null,\n     subnational: '1',\n     state: 'active',\n     has_geodata: false,\n     methodology: 'Other',\n     version: null,\n     is_requestdata_type: false,\n     license_id: 'cc-by-sa',\n     num_of_showcases: 1,\n     type: 'dataset',\n     resources: [ [Object] ],\n     dataset_preview: 'first_resource',\n     num_resources: 1,\n     dataset_source: 'ACLED',\n     tags: [ [Object], [Object], [Object], [Object] ],\n     revision_id: '491de2b1-e8a6-4917-b4c2-e075cd4edd18',\n     groups: [ [Object] ],\n     creator_user_id: '154de241-38d6-47d3-a77f-0a9848a61df3',\n     has_quickcharts: true,\n     methodology_other: '[ACLED\\'s Methodology page](https://www.acleddata.com/resources/methodology/) contains information about how the ACLED team collects, cleans, reviews and checks event data, with a focus on what makes ACLED unique and compatible with other data. This dataset contains information on the specific dates and locations of political violence, the types of event, the groups involved, fatalities and changes in territorial control. Information is recorded on the battles, killings, riots, and recruitment activities of rebels, governments, militias, armed groups, protesters and civilians. \\r\\n\\r\\nAs of early 2015, ACLED has recorded over 100,000 individual events, with ongoing data collection focused on Africa, South Asia and South East Asia. Data can be used for medium- and long-term analysis and mapping of political violence across developing countries through use of historical data from 1997, as well as informing humanitarian and development work in crisis and conflict-affected contexts through realtime data updates and reports. Despite the waning of civil wars across the developing world, ACLED data show that political violence rates have remained relatively stable in the past eighteen years. ACLED does not have a fatality threshold for event inclusion. This means that conflict and demonstration events in ACLED do not have to produce any fatalities in order to be included as a valid event. We use no arbitrary number of deaths to define a conflict.\\n2. ACLED reports fatalities only when a reputable source has relayed that information. Further, researchers seek out information to triangulate – where and when possible – the numbers from any report.\\n3. ACLED uses the most conservative estimate available, and will revise and correct the totals – upward or downward – when better information comes available.\\n\\nACLED advises caution in using all fatality numbers from its, or any other conflict data source. Fatality information is the most biased, and least accurate, part of any conflict report and extreme caution should be employed when using any fatality number to show patterns.',\n     metadata_modified: '2018-11-17T01:17:26.848580',\n     author: null,\n     author_email: null,\n     subnational: '1',\n     state: 'active',\n     has_geodata: false,\n     methodology: 'Other',\n     version: null,\n     is_requestdata_type: false,\n     license_id: 'cc-by-sa',\n     num_of_showcases: 1,\n     type: 'dataset',\n     resources: [ [Object] ],\n     dataset_preview: 'first_resource',\n     num_resources: 1,\n     dataset_source: 'ACLED',\n     tags: [ [Object], [Object], [Object], [Object] ],\n     revision_id: '5a302db7-8f8c-4bc6-aa85-5320941f6735',\n     groups: [ [Object] ],\n     creator_user_id: '154de241-38d6-47d3-a77f-0a9848a61df3',\n     has_quickcharts: true,\n     methodology_other: '[ACLED\\'s Methodology page](https://www.acleddata.com/resources/methodology/) contains information about how the ACLED team collects, cleans, reviews and checks event data, with a focus on what makes ACLED unique and compatible with other data. This dataset contains information on the specific dates and locations of political violence, the types of event, the groups involved, fatalities and changes in territorial control. Information is recorded on the battles, killings, riots, and recruitment activities of rebels, governments, militias, armed groups, protesters and civilians. \\r\\n\\r\\nAs of early 2015, ACLED has recorded over 100,000 individual events, with ongoing data collection focused on Africa, South Asia and South East Asia. Data can be used for medium- and long-term analysis and mapping of political violence across developing countries through use of historical data from 1997, as well as informing humanitarian and development work in crisis and conflict-affected contexts through realtime data updates and reports. Despite the waning of civil wars across the developing world, ACLED data show that political violence rates have remained relatively stable in the past eighteen years. ACLED seeks to support research and work devoted to understanding, predicting and reducing levels of violence and their consequences.',\n        created: '2015-01-09T14:44:54.006612',\n        title: 'Armed Conflict Location & Event Data Project (ACLED)',\n        name: 'acled',\n        is_organization: true,\n        state: 'active',\n        image_url: '',\n        revision_id: 'ca4f1ccc-0a39-4785-af1d-f7257d504829',\n        type: 'organization',\n        id: 'b67e6c74-c185-4f43-b561-0e114a736f19',\n        approval_status: 'approved' },\n     name: 'acled-data-for-mozambique',\n     isopen: true,\n     url: null,\n     notes: 'The ACLED project codes reported information on the type, agents, exact location, date, and other characteristics of political violence events, demonstrations and select politically relevant non-violent events. ACLED does not have a fatality threshold for event inclusion. This means that conflict and demonstration events in ACLED do not have to produce any fatalities in order to be included as a valid event. We use no arbitrary number of deaths to define a conflict.\\n2. ACLED reports fatalities only when a reputable source has relayed that information. Further, researchers seek out information to triangulate – where and when possible – the numbers from any report.\\n3. ACLED uses the most conservative estimate available, and will revise and correct the totals – upward or downward – when better information comes available.\\n\\nACLED advises caution in using all fatality numbers from its, or any other conflict data source. Fatality information is the most biased, and least accurate, part of any conflict report and extreme caution should be employed when using any fatality number to show patterns.',\n     metadata_modified: '2018-11-17T01:15:46.458095',\n     author: null,\n     author_email: null,\n     subnational: '1',\n     state: 'active',\n     has_geodata: false,\n     methodology: 'Other',\n     version: null,\n     is_requestdata_type: false,\n     license_id: 'cc-by-sa',\n     num_of_showcases: 1,\n     type: 'dataset',\n     resources: [ [Object] ],\n     dataset_preview: 'first_resource',\n     num_resources: 1,\n     dataset_source: 'ACLED',\n     tags: [ [Object], [Object], [Object], [Object] ],\n     revision_id: 'e3e3e50f-4884-4a8a-b752-f1f40e21f8cf',\n     groups: [ [Object] ],\n     creator_user_id: '154de241-38d6-47d3-a77f-0a9848a61df3',\n     has_quickcharts: true,\n     methodology_other: '[ACLED\\'s Methodology page](https://www.acleddata.com/resources/methodology/) contains information about how the ACLED team collects, cleans, reviews and checks event data, with a focus on what makes ACLED unique and compatible with other data. This dataset contains information on the specific dates and locations of political violence, the types of event, the groups involved, fatalities and changes in territorial control. Information is recorded on the battles, killings, riots, and recruitment activities of rebels, governments, militias, armed groups, protesters and civilians. \\r\\n\\r\\nAs of early 2015, ACLED has recorded over 100,000 individual events, with ongoing data collection focused on Africa, South Asia and South East Asia. Data can be used for medium- and long-term analysis and mapping of political violence across developing countries through use of historical data from 1997, as well as informing humanitarian and development work in crisis and conflict-affected contexts through realtime data updates and reports. Despite the waning of civil wars across the developing world, ACLED data show that political violence rates have remained relatively stable in the past eighteen years. ACLED seeks to support research and work devoted to understanding, predicting and reducing levels of violence and their consequences.',\n        created: '2015-01-09T14:44:54.006612',\n        title: 'Armed Conflict Location & Event Data Project (ACLED)',\n        name: 'acled',\n        is_organization: true,\n        state: 'active',\n        image_url: '',\n        revision_id: 'ca4f1ccc-0a39-4785-af1d-f7257d504829',\n        type: 'organization',\n        id: 'b67e6c74-c185-4f43-b561-0e114a736f19',\n        approval_status: 'approved' },\n     name: 'acled-data-for-namibia',\n     isopen: true,\n     url: null,\n     notes: 'The ACLED project codes reported information on the type, agents, exact location, date, and other characteristics of political violence events, demonstrations and select politically relevant non-violent events. ACLED does not have a fatality threshold for event inclusion. This means that conflict and demonstration events in ACLED do not have to produce any fatalities in order to be included as a valid event. We use no arbitrary number of deaths to define a conflict.\\n2. ACLED reports fatalities only when a reputable source has relayed that information. Further, researchers seek out information to triangulate – where and when possible – the numbers from any report.\\n3. ACLED uses the most conservative estimate available, and will revise and correct the totals – upward or downward – when better information comes available.\\n\\nACLED advises caution in using all fatality numbers from its, or any other conflict data source. Fatality information is the most biased, and least accurate, part of any conflict report and extreme caution should be employed when using any fatality number to show patterns.',\n     metadata_modified: '2018-11-17T01:17:16.052475',\n     author: null,\n     author_email: null,\n     subnational: '1',\n     state: 'active',\n     has_geodata: false,\n     methodology: 'Other',\n     version: null,\n     is_requestdata_type: false,\n     license_id: 'cc-by-sa',\n     num_of_showcases: 1,\n     type: 'dataset',\n     resources: [ [Object] ],\n     dataset_preview: 'first_resource',\n     num_resources: 1,\n     dataset_source: 'ACLED',\n     tags: [ [Object], [Object], [Object], [Object] ],\n     revision_id: '14011dc8-5ee5-45ad-8020-129d268c2347',\n     groups: [ [Object] ],\n     creator_user_id: '154de241-38d6-47d3-a77f-0a9848a61df3',\n     has_quickcharts: true,\n     methodology_other: '[ACLED\\'s Methodology page](https://www.acleddata.com/resources/methodology/) contains information about how the ACLED team collects, cleans, reviews and checks event data, with a focus on what makes ACLED unique and compatible with other data. Information is recorded on the battles, killings, riots, and recruitment activities of rebels, governments, militias, armed groups, protesters and civilians. \\r\\n\\r\\nAs of early 2015, ACLED has recorded over 100,000 individual events, with ongoing data collection focused on Africa, South Asia and South East Asia. Data can be used for medium- and long-term analysis and mapping of political violence across developing countries through use of historical data from 1997, as well as informing humanitarian and development work in crisis and conflict-affected contexts through realtime data updates and reports. Despite the waning of civil wars across the developing world, ACLED data show that political violence rates have remained relatively stable in the past eighteen years. High spatial resolution estimates of population counts per 100x100m grid cell for 2015 were recently constructed for Latin American and Caribbean countries [1]. With consistent subnational data on sex and age structures, as well as subnational age-specific fertility rate data across the Americas currently unavailable for fully replicating the approaches of [2], national level adjustments were made to construct pregnancy counts. Data on estimated total numbers of births [5] and pregnancies [6] occurring annually in 2012 were assembled for all Latin American study countries, as well as births in 2015 [5]. As no 2015 pregnancies estimates exist at present, the ratios of births to pregnancies for each country in the Americas were calculated using the 2012 estimates, and then these were applied to the 2015 births numbers to obtain 2015 estimates of annual pregnancy numbers per-country. This made the assumption that the per-country births:pregnancies ratios remained the same in 2015 as they were in 2012. The 100m spatial resolution gridded population totals data were aggregated to 1km spatial resolution, and the per-country totals were linearly adjusted to match the 2015 pregnancy estimates, to create gridded estimates of numbers of pregnancies across the Americas. Ongoing work is focused on refining these estimates using subnational age-sex structures and age-specific fertility rates, following previous approaches [1,2,3], to better account for subnational variations within countries.',\n     metadata_modified: '2017-01-20T09:59:24.956773',\n     author: '',\n     author_email: '',\n     subnational: '1',\n     state: 'active',\n     has_geodata: true,\n     methodology: 'Direct Observational Data/Anecdotal Data',\n     version: null,\n     is_requestdata_type: false,\n     license_id: 'cc-by-igo',\n     num_of_showcases: 0,\n     type: 'dataset',\n     resources: [ [Object], [Object] ],\n     dataset_preview: 'first_resource',\n     num_resources: 2,\n     dataset_source: 'University of Southampton',\n     tags: [ [Object], [Object], [Object], [Object], [Object] ],\n     revision_id: 'ebf35e62-65b1-45b0-914f-4638c77bf1c6',\n     groups: [ [Object] ],\n     creator_user_id: '23b4c749-bd1b-499c-a8f1-8d76240a534d',\n     has_quickcharts: false,\n     relationships_as_subject: [],\n     total_res_downloads: 138,\n     organization: \n      { description: 'The WorldPop project was initiated in October 2013 to combine the AfriPop, AsiaPop and AmeriPop population mapping projects. ACLED does not have a fatality threshold for event inclusion. This means that conflict and demonstration events in ACLED do not have to produce any fatalities in order to be included as a valid event. We use no arbitrary number of deaths to define a conflict.\\n2. ACLED reports fatalities only when a reputable source has relayed that information. Further, researchers seek out information to triangulate – where and when possible – the numbers from any report.\\n3. ACLED uses the most conservative estimate available, and will revise and correct the totals – upward or downward – when better information comes available.\\n\\nACLED advises caution in using all fatality numbers from its, or any other conflict data source. Fatality information is the most biased, and least accurate, part of any conflict report and extreme caution should be employed when using any fatality number to show patterns.',\n     metadata_modified: '2018-11-17T01:17:04.899905',\n     author: null,\n     author_email: null,\n     subnational: '1',\n     state: 'active',\n     has_geodata: false,\n     methodology: 'Other',\n     version: null,\n     is_requestdata_type: false,\n     license_id: 'cc-by-sa',\n     num_of_showcases: 1,\n     type: 'dataset',\n     resources: [ [Object] ],\n     dataset_preview: 'first_resource',\n     num_resources: 1,\n     dataset_source: 'ACLED',\n     tags: [ [Object], [Object], [Object], [Object] ],\n     revision_id: '20dfb2ef-8456-409d-a41b-48f565d59802',\n     groups: [ [Object] ],\n     creator_user_id: '154de241-38d6-47d3-a77f-0a9848a61df3',\n     has_quickcharts: true,\n     methodology_other: '[ACLED\\'s Methodology page](https://www.acleddata.com/resources/methodology/) contains information about how the ACLED team collects, cleans, reviews and checks event data, with a focus on what makes ACLED unique and compatible with other data. Information is recorded on the battles, killings, riots, and recruitment activities of rebels, governments, militias, armed groups, protesters and civilians. \\r\\n\\r\\nAs of early 2015, ACLED has recorded over 100,000 individual events, with ongoing data collection focused on Africa, South Asia and South East Asia. Data can be used for medium- and long-term analysis and mapping of political violence across developing countries through use of historical data from 1997, as well as informing humanitarian and development work in crisis and conflict-affected contexts through realtime data updates and reports. Despite the waning of civil wars across the developing world, ACLED data show that political violence rates have remained relatively stable in the past eighteen years. ACLED does not have a fatality threshold for event inclusion. This means that conflict and demonstration events in ACLED do not have to produce any fatalities in order to be included as a valid event. We use no arbitrary number of deaths to define a conflict.\\n2. ACLED reports fatalities only when a reputable source has relayed that information. Further, researchers seek out information to triangulate – where and when possible – the numbers from any report.\\n3. ACLED uses the most conservative estimate available, and will revise and correct the totals – upward or downward – when better information comes available.\\n\\nACLED advises caution in using all fatality numbers from its, or any other conflict data source. Fatality information is the most biased, and least accurate, part of any conflict report and extreme caution should be employed when using any fatality number to show patterns.',\n     metadata_modified: '2018-11-17T01:16:48.051310',\n     author: null,\n     author_email: null,\n     subnational: '1',\n     state: 'active',\n     has_geodata: false,\n     methodology: 'Other',\n     version: null,\n     is_requestdata_type: false,\n     license_id: 'cc-by-sa',\n     num_of_showcases: 1,\n     type: 'dataset',\n     resources: [ [Object] ],\n     dataset_preview: 'first_resource',\n     num_resources: 1,\n     dataset_source: 'ACLED',\n     tags: [ [Object], [Object], [Object], [Object] ],\n     revision_id: 'ffb0d4a2-7c2c-45b1-a1ae-5368f213fba8',\n     groups: [ [Object] ],\n     creator_user_id: '154de241-38d6-47d3-a77f-0a9848a61df3',\n     has_quickcharts: true,\n     methodology_other: '[ACLED\\'s Methodology page](https://www.acleddata.com/resources/methodology/) contains information about how the ACLED team collects, cleans, reviews and checks event data, with a focus on what makes ACLED unique and compatible with other data. Information is recorded on the battles, killings, riots, and recruitment activities of rebels, governments, militias, armed groups, protesters and civilians. \\r\\n\\r\\nAs of early 2015, ACLED has recorded over 100,000 individual events, with ongoing data collection focused on Africa, South Asia and South East Asia. Data can be used for medium- and long-term analysis and mapping of political violence across developing countries through use of historical data from 1997, as well as informing humanitarian and development work in crisis and conflict-affected contexts through realtime data updates and reports. Despite the waning of civil wars across the developing world, ACLED data show that political violence rates have remained relatively stable in the past eighteen years. ACLED does not have a fatality threshold for event inclusion. This means that conflict and demonstration events in ACLED do not have to produce any fatalities in order to be included as a valid event. We use no arbitrary number of deaths to define a conflict.\\n2. ACLED reports fatalities only when a reputable source has relayed that information. Further, researchers seek out information to triangulate – where and when possible – the numbers from any report.\\n3. ACLED uses the most conservative estimate available, and will revise and correct the totals – upward or downward – when better information comes available.\\n\\nACLED advises caution in using all fatality numbers from its, or any other conflict data source. Fatality information is the most biased, and least accurate, part of any conflict report and extreme caution should be employed when using any fatality number to show patterns.',\n     metadata_modified: '2018-11-17T01:16:38.280252',\n     author: null,\n     author_email: null,\n     subnational: '1',\n     state: 'active',\n     has_geodata: false,\n     methodology: 'Other',\n     version: null,\n     is_requestdata_type: false,\n     license_id: 'cc-by-sa',\n     num_of_showcases: 1,\n     type: 'dataset',\n     resources: [ [Object] ],\n     dataset_preview: 'first_resource',\n     num_resources: 1,\n     dataset_source: 'ACLED',\n     tags: [ [Object], [Object], [Object], [Object] ],\n     revision_id: '1e75710e-2ece-4d77-8601-d59f1c971447',\n     groups: [ [Object] ],\n     creator_user_id: '154de241-38d6-47d3-a77f-0a9848a61df3',\n     has_quickcharts: true,\n     methodology_other: '[ACLED\\'s Methodology page](https://www.acleddata.com/resources/methodology/) contains information about how the ACLED team collects, cleans, reviews and checks event data, with a focus on what makes ACLED unique and compatible with other data. This dataset contains information on the specific dates and locations of political violence, the types of event, the groups involved, fatalities and changes in territorial control. Information is recorded on the battles, killings, riots, and recruitment activities of rebels, governments, militias, armed groups, protesters and civilians. \\r\\n\\r\\nAs of early 2015, ACLED has recorded over 100,000 individual events, with ongoing data collection focused on Africa, South Asia and South East Asia. Data can be used for medium- and long-term analysis and mapping of political violence across developing countries through use of historical data from 1997, as well as informing humanitarian and development work in crisis and conflict-affected contexts through realtime data updates and reports. Despite the waning of civil wars across the developing world, ACLED data show that political violence rates have remained relatively stable in the past eighteen years. ACLED seeks to support research and work devoted to understanding, predicting and reducing levels of violence and their consequences.',\n        created: '2015-01-09T14:44:54.006612',\n        title: 'Armed Conflict Location & Event Data Project (ACLED)',\n        name: 'acled',\n        is_organization: true,\n        state: 'active',\n        image_url: '',\n        revision_id: 'ca4f1ccc-0a39-4785-af1d-f7257d504829',\n        type: 'organization',\n        id: 'b67e6c74-c185-4f43-b561-0e114a736f19',\n        approval_status: 'approved' },\n     name: 'acled-data-for-oman',\n     isopen: true,\n     url: null,\n     notes: 'The ACLED project codes reported information on the type, agents, exact location, date, and other characteristics of political violence events, demonstrations and select politically relevant non-violent events. ACLED does not have a fatality threshold for event inclusion. This means that conflict and demonstration events in ACLED do not have to produce any fatalities in order to be included as a valid event. We use no arbitrary number of deaths to define a conflict.\\n2. ACLED reports fatalities only when a reputable source has relayed that information. Further, researchers seek out information to triangulate – where and when possible – the numbers from any report.\\n3. ACLED uses the most conservative estimate available, and will revise and correct the totals – upward or downward – when better information comes available.\\n\\nACLED advises caution in using all fatality numbers from its, or any other conflict data source. Fatality information is the most biased, and least accurate, part of any conflict report and extreme caution should be employed when using any fatality number to show patterns.',\n     metadata_modified: '2018-11-17T01:15:40.031210',\n     author: null,\n     author_email: null,\n     subnational: '1',\n     state: 'active',\n     has_geodata: false,\n     methodology: 'Other',\n     version: null,\n     is_requestdata_type: false,\n     license_id: 'cc-by-sa',\n     num_of_showcases: 1,\n     type: 'dataset',\n     resources: [ [Object] ],\n     dataset_preview: 'first_resource',\n     num_resources: 1,\n     dataset_source: 'ACLED',\n     tags: [ [Object], [Object], [Object], [Object] ],\n     revision_id: 'c070c3c0-37d7-4fde-9097-e4c386a390ae',\n     groups: [ [Object] ],\n     creator_user_id: '154de241-38d6-47d3-a77f-0a9848a61df3',\n     has_quickcharts: true,\n     methodology_other: '[ACLED\\'s Methodology page](https://www.acleddata.com/resources/methodology/) contains information about how the ACLED team collects, cleans, reviews and checks event data, with a focus on what makes ACLED unique and compatible with other data. Information is recorded on the battles, killings, riots, and recruitment activities of rebels, governments, militias, armed groups, protesters and civilians. \\r\\n\\r\\nAs of early 2015, ACLED has recorded over 100,000 individual events, with ongoing data collection focused on Africa, South Asia and South East Asia. Data can be used for medium- and long-term analysis and mapping of political violence across developing countries through use of historical data from 1997, as well as informing humanitarian and development work in crisis and conflict-affected contexts through realtime data updates and reports. Despite the waning of civil wars across the developing world, ACLED data show that political violence rates have remained relatively stable in the past eighteen years. ACLED does not have a fatality threshold for event inclusion. This means that conflict and demonstration events in ACLED do not have to produce any fatalities in order to be included as a valid event. We use no arbitrary number of deaths to define a conflict.\\n2. ACLED reports fatalities only when a reputable source has relayed that information. Further, researchers seek out information to triangulate – where and when possible – the numbers from any report.\\n3. ACLED uses the most conservative estimate available, and will revise and correct the totals – upward or downward – when better information comes available.\\n\\nACLED advises caution in using all fatality numbers from its, or any other conflict data source. Fatality information is the most biased, and least accurate, part of any conflict report and extreme caution should be employed when using any fatality number to show patterns.',\n     metadata_modified: '2018-07-16T15:39:31.558163',\n     author: null,\n     author_email: null,\n     subnational: '1',\n     state: 'active',\n     has_geodata: false,\n     methodology: 'Other',\n     version: null,\n     is_requestdata_type: false,\n     license_id: 'cc-by-sa',\n     num_of_showcases: 1,\n     type: 'dataset',\n     resources: [ [Object] ],\n     dataset_preview: 'first_resource',\n     num_resources: 1,\n     dataset_source: 'ACLED',\n     tags: [ [Object], [Object], [Object], [Object] ],\n     revision_id: '2d45ac52-42bc-496c-955b-d95a7c9384f0',\n     groups: [ [Object] ],\n     creator_user_id: '154de241-38d6-47d3-a77f-0a9848a61df3',\n     has_quickcharts: true,\n     methodology_other: '[ACLED\\'s Methodology page](https://www.acleddata.com/resources/methodology/) contains information about how the ACLED team collects, cleans, reviews and checks event data, with a focus on what makes ACLED unique and compatible with other data. Information is recorded on the battles, killings, riots, and recruitment activities of rebels, governments, militias, armed groups, protesters and civilians. \\r\\n\\r\\nAs of early 2015, ACLED has recorded over 100,000 individual events, with ongoing data collection focused on Africa, South Asia and South East Asia. Data can be used for medium- and long-term analysis and mapping of political violence across developing countries through use of historical data from 1997, as well as informing humanitarian and development work in crisis and conflict-affected contexts through realtime data updates and reports. Despite the waning of civil wars across the developing world, ACLED data show that political violence rates have remained relatively stable in the past eighteen years. The southern Africa region has fewer protracted humanitarian crises, but is prone to drought and floods. For this reason, OCHA does not have country offices in the region.
