ACLED does not have a fatality threshold for event inclusion. This means that conflict and demonstration events in ACLED do not have to produce any fatalities in order to be included as a valid event. We use no arbitrary number of deaths to define a conflict.\\n2. ACLED reports fatalities only when a reputable source has relayed that information. Further, researchers seek out information to triangulate – where and when possible – the numbers from any report.\\n3. ACLED uses the most conservative estimate available, and will revise and correct the totals – upward or downward – when better information comes available.\\n\\nACLED advises caution in using all fatality numbers from its, or any other conflict data source. Fatality information is the most biased, and least accurate, part of any conflict report and extreme caution should be employed when using any fatality number to show patterns.',\n     metadata_modified: '2018-11-17T01:17:11.952476',\n     author: null,\n     author_email: null,\n     subnational: '1',\n     state: 'active',\n     has_geodata: false,\n     methodology: 'Other',\n     version: null,\n     is_requestdata_type: false,\n     license_id: 'cc-by-sa',\n     num_of_showcases: 1,\n     type: 'dataset',\n     resources: [ [Object] ],\n     dataset_preview: 'first_resource',\n     num_resources: 1,\n     dataset_source: 'ACLED',\n     tags: [ [Object], [Object], [Object], [Object] ],\n     revision_id: 'e6e01b59-33e5-4b28-a899-77351ffe1969',\n     groups: [ [Object] ],\n     creator_user_id: '154de241-38d6-47d3-a77f-0a9848a61df3',\n     has_quickcharts: true,\n     methodology_other: '[ACLED\\'s Methodology page](https://www.acleddata.com/resources/methodology/) contains information about how the ACLED team collects, cleans, reviews and checks event data, with a focus on what makes ACLED unique and compatible with other data. This dataset contains information on the specific dates and locations of political violence, the types of event, the groups involved, fatalities and changes in territorial control. Information is recorded on the battles, killings, riots, and recruitment activities of rebels, governments, militias, armed groups, protesters and civilians. \\r\\n\\r\\nAs of early 2015, ACLED has recorded over 100,000 individual events, with ongoing data collection focused on Africa, South Asia and South East Asia. Data can be used for medium- and long-term analysis and mapping of political violence across developing countries through use of historical data from 1997, as well as informing humanitarian and development work in crisis and conflict-affected contexts through realtime data updates and reports. Despite the waning of civil wars across the developing world, ACLED data show that political violence rates have remained relatively stable in the past eighteen years. ACLED does not have a fatality threshold for event inclusion. This means that conflict and demonstration events in ACLED do not have to produce any fatalities in order to be included as a valid event. We use no arbitrary number of deaths to define a conflict.\\n2. ACLED reports fatalities only when a reputable source has relayed that information. Further, researchers seek out information to triangulate – where and when possible – the numbers from any report.\\n3. ACLED uses the most conservative estimate available, and will revise and correct the totals – upward or downward – when better information comes available.\\n\\nACLED advises caution in using all fatality numbers from its, or any other conflict data source. Information is recorded on the battles, killings, riots, and recruitment activities of rebels, governments, militias, armed groups, protesters and civilians. \\r\\n\\r\\nAs of early 2015, ACLED has recorded over 100,000 individual events, with ongoing data collection focused on Africa, South Asia and South East Asia. Data can be used for medium- and long-term analysis and mapping of political violence across developing countries through use of historical data from 1997, as well as informing humanitarian and development work in crisis and conflict-affected contexts through realtime data updates and reports. ACLED does not have a fatality threshold for event inclusion. This means that conflict and demonstration events in ACLED do not have to produce any fatalities in order to be included as a valid event. We use no arbitrary number of deaths to define a conflict.\\n2. ACLED reports fatalities only when a reputable source has relayed that information. Further, researchers seek out information to triangulate – where and when possible – the numbers from any report.\\n3. ACLED uses the most conservative estimate available, and will revise and correct the totals – upward or downward – when better information comes available.\\n\\nACLED advises caution in using all fatality numbers from its, or any other conflict data source. ACLED does not have a fatality threshold for event inclusion. This means that conflict and demonstration events in ACLED do not have to produce any fatalities in order to be included as a valid event. We use no arbitrary number of deaths to define a conflict.\\n2. ACLED reports fatalities only when a reputable source has relayed that information. Further, researchers seek out information to triangulate – where and when possible – the numbers from any report.\\n3. ACLED uses the most conservative estimate available, and will revise and correct the totals – upward or downward – when better information comes available.\\n\\nACLED advises caution in using all fatality numbers from its, or any other conflict data source. Fatality information is the most biased, and least accurate, part of any conflict report and extreme caution should be employed when using any fatality number to show patterns.',\n     metadata_modified: '2018-11-17T01:15:43.361316',\n     author: null,\n     author_email: null,\n     subnational: '1',\n     state: 'active',\n     has_geodata: false,\n     methodology: 'Other',\n     version: null,\n     is_requestdata_type: false,\n     license_id: 'cc-by-sa',\n     num_of_showcases: 1,\n     type: 'dataset',\n     resources: [ [Object] ],\n     dataset_preview: 'first_resource',\n     num_resources: 1,\n     dataset_source: 'ACLED',\n     tags: [ [Object], [Object], [Object], [Object] ],\n     revision_id: 'c14695c4-a27b-41a6-a418-89c70d72b2e0',\n     groups: [ [Object] ],\n     creator_user_id: '154de241-38d6-47d3-a77f-0a9848a61df3',\n     has_quickcharts: true,\n     methodology_other: '[ACLED\\'s Methodology page](https://www.acleddata.com/resources/methodology/) contains information about how the ACLED team collects, cleans, reviews and checks event data, with a focus on what makes ACLED unique and compatible with other data. This dataset contains information on the specific dates and locations of political violence, the types of event, the groups involved, fatalities and changes in territorial control. Information is recorded on the battles, killings, riots, and recruitment activities of rebels, governments, militias, armed groups, protesters and civilians. \\r\\n\\r\\nAs of early 2015, ACLED has recorded over 100,000 individual events, with ongoing data collection focused on Africa, South Asia and South East Asia. Data can be used for medium- and long-term analysis and mapping of political violence across developing countries through use of historical data from 1997, as well as informing humanitarian and development work in crisis and conflict-affected contexts through realtime data updates and reports. Despite the waning of civil wars across the developing world, ACLED data show that political violence rates have remained relatively stable in the past eighteen years. ACLED seeks to support research and work devoted to understanding, predicting and reducing levels of violence and their consequences.',\n        created: '2015-01-09T14:44:54.006612',\n        title: 'Armed Conflict Location & Event Data Project (ACLED)',\n        name: 'acled',\n        is_organization: true,\n        state: 'active',\n        image_url: '',\n        revision_id: 'ca4f1ccc-0a39-4785-af1d-f7257d504829',\n        type: 'organization',\n        id: 'b67e6c74-c185-4f43-b561-0e114a736f19',\n        approval_status: 'approved' },\n     name: 'acled-data-for-sierra-leone',\n     isopen: true,\n     url: null,\n     notes: 'The ACLED project codes reported information on the type, agents, exact location, date, and other characteristics of political violence events, demonstrations and select politically relevant non-violent events. ACLED does not have a fatality threshold for event inclusion. This means that conflict and demonstration events in ACLED do not have to produce any fatalities in order to be included as a valid event. We use no arbitrary number of deaths to define a conflict.\\n2. ACLED reports fatalities only when a reputable source has relayed that information. Further, researchers seek out information to triangulate – where and when possible – the numbers from any report.\\n3. ACLED uses the most conservative estimate available, and will revise and correct the totals – upward or downward – when better information comes available.\\n\\nACLED advises caution in using all fatality numbers from its, or any other conflict data source. Fatality information is the most biased, and least accurate, part of any conflict report and extreme caution should be employed when using any fatality number to show patterns.',\n     metadata_modified: '2018-11-17T01:17:24.150828',\n     author: null,\n     author_email: null,\n     subnational: '1',\n     state: 'active',\n     has_geodata: false,\n     methodology: 'Other',\n     version: null,\n     is_requestdata_type: false,\n     license_id: 'cc-by-sa',\n     num_of_showcases: 1,\n     type: 'dataset',\n     resources: [ [Object] ],\n     dataset_preview: 'first_resource',\n     num_resources: 1,\n     dataset_source: 'ACLED',\n     tags: [ [Object], [Object], [Object], [Object] ],\n     revision_id: '2af182c8-1d15-4cea-8393-fc6eb27a1b3b',\n     groups: [ [Object] ],\n     creator_user_id: '154de241-38d6-47d3-a77f-0a9848a61df3',\n     has_quickcharts: true,\n     methodology_other: '[ACLED\\'s Methodology page](https://www.acleddata.com/resources/methodology/) contains information about how the ACLED team collects, cleans, reviews and checks event data, with a focus on what makes ACLED unique and compatible with other data. The process of ACLED coding assures that it is accurate, comprehensive, transparent and regularly updated. This dataset contains information on the specific dates and locations of political violence, the types of event, the groups involved, fatalities and changes in territorial control. Information is recorded on the battles, killings, riots, and recruitment activities of rebels, governments, militias, armed groups, protesters and civilians. \\r\\n\\r\\nAs of early 2015, ACLED has recorded over 100,000 individual events, with ongoing data collection focused on Africa, South Asia and South East Asia. Data can be used for medium- and long-term analysis and mapping of political violence across developing countries through use of historical data from 1997, as well as informing humanitarian and development work in crisis and conflict-affected contexts through realtime data updates and reports. Despite the waning of civil wars across the developing world, ACLED data show that political violence rates have remained relatively stable in the past eighteen years. ACLED seeks to support research and work devoted to understanding, predicting and reducing levels of violence and their consequences.',\n        created: '2015-01-09T14:44:54.006612',\n        title: 'Armed Conflict Location & Event Data Project (ACLED)',\n        name: 'acled',\n        is_organization: true,\n        state: 'active',\n        image_url: '',\n        revision_id: 'ca4f1ccc-0a39-4785-af1d-f7257d504829',\n        type: 'organization',\n        id: 'b67e6c74-c185-4f43-b561-0e114a736f19',\n        approval_status: 'approved' },\n     name: 'acled-data-for-somalia',\n     isopen: true,\n     url: null,\n     notes: 'The ACLED project codes reported information on the type, agents, exact location, date, and other characteristics of political violence events, demonstrations and select politically relevant non-violent events. For this reason, OCHA maintains country presences in Burundi, DRC, Eritrea, Ethiopia, Kenya, Somalia, South Sudan and Sudan. The southern Africa region has fewer protracted humanitarian crises, but is prone to drought and floods. For this reason, OCHA does not have country offices in the region. In both regions the 2015-2016 El Nino weather phenomenon continues to have a significant humanitarian impact.\\r\\n\\r\\nFor those countries where OCHA does not have a presence, it is essential that OCHA can deploy from the regional hub swiftly and effectively in times of emergency, and to otherwise ensure preparedness for potential crises. OCHA works closely with local authorities and partners to bolster national disaster preparedness in these countries and supports response.\\r\\n\\r\\nWhether we’re mobilizing relief money or raising awareness of forgotten crises, it’s our mandate to keep world attention focused on humanitarian issues. For this reason, we produce and release timely regional reporting and analytical products to strengthen the humanitarian case and highlight the needs of the most vulnerable in the region. OCHA ROSEA also provides a platform for the analysis of cross-border issues of humanitarian concern, such as facilitating multi-country preparedness and planning consultations. OCHA ROSEA also works to strengthen collaboration on emergency preparedness and response with regional bodies, such as the Intergovernmental Authority on Development (IGAD) in eastern Africa and the Southern Africa Development Community (SADC) in southern Africa.',\n        created: '2014-04-28T17:49:00.350372',\n        title: 'OCHA ROSEA',\n        name: 'ocha-rosea',\n        is_organization: true,\n        state: 'active',\n        image_url: '',\n        revision_id: '31d22726-56ec-47c1-a72b-3ee663e9e2d0',\n        type: 'organization',\n        id: '37a0c6e3-3bcd-4457-aa81-6ddeb99dd203',\n        approval_status: 'approved' },\n     name: 'ethiopia-hiv-prevalence',\n     isopen: false,\n     url: null,\n     notes: 'Data has been sourced from the United Nations AIDS Epidemological Fact sheet for Ethiopia.',\n     owner_org: '37a0c6e3-3bcd-4457-aa81-6ddeb99dd203',\n     has_showcases: false,\n     pageviews_last_14_days: 4,\n     title: 'Ethiopia HIV Prevalence 2012',\n     package_creator: 'joshuambai' } }","time":"2018-11-19T16:14:55.541Z","v":0}

ACLED does not have a fatality threshold for event inclusion. This means that conflict and demonstration events in ACLED do not have to produce any fatalities in order to be included as a valid event. We use no arbitrary number of deaths to define a conflict.\\n2. ACLED reports fatalities only when a reputable source has relayed that information. Further, researchers seek out information to triangulate – where and when possible – the numbers from any report.\\n3. ACLED uses the most conservative estimate available, and will revise and correct the totals – upward or downward – when better information comes available.\\n\\nACLED advises caution in using all fatality numbers from its, or any other conflict data source. Information is recorded on the battles, killings, riots, and recruitment activities of rebels, governments, militias, armed groups, protesters and civilians. \\r\\n\\r\\nAs of early 2015, ACLED has recorded over 100,000 individual events, with ongoing data collection focused on Africa, South Asia and South East Asia. ACLED does not have a fatality threshold for event inclusion. This means that conflict and demonstration events in ACLED do not have to produce any fatalities in order to be included as a valid event. We use no arbitrary number of deaths to define a conflict.\\n2. ACLED reports fatalities only when a reputable source has relayed that information. Further, researchers seek out information to triangulate – where and when possible – the numbers from any report.\\n3. ACLED uses the most conservative estimate available, and will revise and correct the totals – upward or downward – when better information comes available.\\n\\nACLED advises caution in using all fatality numbers from its, or any other conflict data source. Fatality information is the most biased, and least accurate, part of any conflict report and extreme caution should be employed when using any fatality number to show patterns.',\n     metadata_modified: '2018-11-17T01:16:15.923024',\n     author: null,\n     author_email: null,\n     subnational: '1',\n     state: 'active',\n     has_geodata: false,\n     methodology: 'Other',\n     version: null,\n     is_requestdata_type: false,\n     license_id: 'cc-by-sa',\n     num_of_showcases: 1,\n     type: 'dataset',\n     resources: [ [Object] ],\n     dataset_preview: 'first_resource',\n     num_resources: 1,\n     dataset_source: 'ACLED',\n     tags: [ [Object], [Object], [Object], [Object] ],\n     revision_id: 'b044d9a8-4c88-4acb-91dc-f708de9e001b',\n     groups: [ [Object] ],\n     creator_user_id: '154de241-38d6-47d3-a77f-0a9848a61df3',\n     has_quickcharts: true,\n     methodology_other: '[ACLED\\'s Methodology page](https://www.acleddata.com/resources/methodology/) contains information about how the ACLED team collects, cleans, reviews and checks event data, with a focus on what makes ACLED unique and compatible with other data. This dataset contains information on the specific dates and locations of political violence, the types of event, the groups involved, fatalities and changes in territorial control. Information is recorded on the battles, killings, riots, and recruitment activities of rebels, governments, militias, armed groups, protesters and civilians. \\r\\n\\r\\nAs of early 2015, ACLED has recorded over 100,000 individual events, with ongoing data collection focused on Africa, South Asia and South East Asia. Data can be used for medium- and long-term analysis and mapping of political violence across developing countries through use of historical data from 1997, as well as informing humanitarian and development work in crisis and conflict-affected contexts through realtime data updates and reports. Despite the waning of civil wars across the developing world, ACLED data show that political violence rates have remained relatively stable in the past eighteen years. ACLED seeks to support research and work devoted to understanding, predicting and reducing levels of violence and their consequences.',\n        created: '2015-01-09T14:44:54.006612',\n        title: 'Armed Conflict Location & Event Data Project (ACLED)',\n        name: 'acled',\n        is_organization: true,\n        state: 'active',\n        image_url: '',\n        revision_id: 'ca4f1ccc-0a39-4785-af1d-f7257d504829',\n        type: 'organization',\n        id: 'b67e6c74-c185-4f43-b561-0e114a736f19',\n        approval_status: 'approved' },\n     name: 'acled-data-for-south-sudan',\n     isopen: true,\n     url: null,\n     notes: 'The ACLED project codes reported information on the type, agents, exact location, date, and other characteristics of political violence events, demonstrations and select politically relevant non-violent events. ACLED does not have a fatality threshold for event inclusion. This means that conflict and demonstration events in ACLED do not have to produce any fatalities in order to be included as a valid event. We use no arbitrary number of deaths to define a conflict.\\n2. ACLED reports fatalities only when a reputable source has relayed that information. Further, researchers seek out information to triangulate – where and when possible – the numbers from any report.\\n3. ACLED uses the most conservative estimate available, and will revise and correct the totals – upward or downward – when better information comes available.\\n\\nACLED advises caution in using all fatality numbers from its, or any other conflict data source. ACLED does not have a fatality threshold for event inclusion. This means that conflict and demonstration events in ACLED do not have to produce any fatalities in order to be included as a valid event. We use no arbitrary number of deaths to define a conflict.\\n2. ACLED reports fatalities only when a reputable source has relayed that information. Further, researchers seek out information to triangulate – where and when possible – the numbers from any report.\\n3. ACLED uses the most conservative estimate available, and will revise and correct the totals – upward or downward – when better information comes available.\\n\\nACLED advises caution in using all fatality numbers from its, or any other conflict data source. Fatality information is the most biased, and least accurate, part of any conflict report and extreme caution should be employed when using any fatality number to show patterns.',\n     metadata_modified: '2018-11-17T01:15:58.158829',\n     author: null,\n     author_email: null,\n     subnational: '1',\n     state: 'active',\n     has_geodata: false,\n     methodology: 'Other',\n     version: null,\n     is_requestdata_type: false,\n     license_id: 'cc-by-sa',\n     num_of_showcases: 1,\n     type: 'dataset',\n     resources: [ [Object] ],\n     dataset_preview: 'first_resource',\n     num_resources: 1,\n     dataset_source: 'ACLED',\n     tags: [ [Object], [Object], [Object], [Object] ],\n     revision_id: '195b45f6-c097-4c08-8850-3a1a79904b54',\n     groups: [ [Object] ],\n     creator_user_id: '154de241-38d6-47d3-a77f-0a9848a61df3',\n     has_quickcharts: true,\n     methodology_other: '[ACLED\\'s Methodology page](https://www.acleddata.com/resources/methodology/) contains information about how the ACLED team collects, cleans, reviews and checks event data, with a focus on what makes ACLED unique and compatible with other data. This dataset contains information on the specific dates and locations of political violence, the types of event, the groups involved, fatalities and changes in territorial control. Information is recorded on the battles, killings, riots, and recruitment activities of rebels, governments, militias, armed groups, protesters and civilians. \\r\\n\\r\\nAs of early 2015, ACLED has recorded over 100,000 individual events, with ongoing data collection focused on Africa, South Asia and South East Asia. Data can be used for medium- and long-term analysis and mapping of political violence across developing countries through use of historical data from 1997, as well as informing humanitarian and development work in crisis and conflict-affected contexts through realtime data updates and reports. Despite the waning of civil wars across the developing world, ACLED data show that political violence rates have remained relatively stable in the past eighteen years. ACLED does not have a fatality threshold for event inclusion. This means that conflict and demonstration events in ACLED do not have to produce any fatalities in order to be included as a valid event. We use no arbitrary number of deaths to define a conflict.\\n2. ACLED reports fatalities only when a reputable source has relayed that information. Further, researchers seek out information to triangulate – where and when possible – the numbers from any report.\\n3. ACLED uses the most conservative estimate available, and will revise and correct the totals – upward or downward – when better information comes available.\\n\\nACLED advises caution in using all fatality numbers from its, or any other conflict data source. Fatality information is the most biased, and least accurate, part of any conflict report and extreme caution should be employed when using any fatality number to show patterns.',\n     metadata_modified: '2018-11-17T01:17:17.383487',\n     author: null,\n     author_email: null,\n     subnational: '1',\n     state: 'active',\n     has_geodata: false,\n     methodology: 'Other',\n     version: null,\n     is_requestdata_type: false,\n     license_id: 'cc-by-sa',\n     num_of_showcases: 1,\n     type: 'dataset',\n     resources: [ [Object] ],\n     dataset_preview: 'first_resource',\n     num_resources: 1,\n     dataset_source: 'ACLED',\n     tags: [ [Object], [Object], [Object], [Object] ],\n     revision_id: 'a093ff4c-9b0a-4cda-96ff-54d31ee1c702',\n     groups: [ [Object] ],\n     creator_user_id: '154de241-38d6-47d3-a77f-0a9848a61df3',\n     has_quickcharts: true,\n     methodology_other: '[ACLED\\'s Methodology page](https://www.acleddata.com/resources/methodology/) contains information about how the ACLED team collects, cleans, reviews and checks event data, with a focus on what makes ACLED unique and compatible with other data. This dataset contains information on the specific dates and locations of political violence, the types of event, the groups involved, fatalities and changes in territorial control. Information is recorded on the battles, killings, riots, and recruitment activities of rebels, governments, militias, armed groups, protesters and civilians. \\r\\n\\r\\nAs of early 2015, ACLED has recorded over 100,000 individual events, with ongoing data collection focused on Africa, South Asia and South East Asia. Data can be used for medium- and long-term analysis and mapping of political violence across developing countries through use of historical data from 1997, as well as informing humanitarian and development work in crisis and conflict-affected contexts through realtime data updates and reports. Despite the waning of civil wars across the developing world, ACLED data show that political violence rates have remained relatively stable in the past eighteen years.
